    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, it sounds like your tomato plants are experiencing a case of \"nitrogen deficiency,\" which can cause the leaves to turn yellow, especially the older, lower leaves. Nitrogen is a crucial nutrient for plant growth, and if it's being used up too quickly or not being replenished, your plants won't be able to produce enough chlorophyll, which gives leaves their green color.\n\nTo fix this issue, you can try adding a nitrogen-rich fertilizer to your soil. Look for a fertilizer with a high nitrogen content, such as one with a higher first number in the N-P-K ratio (e.g., 10-10-10 or 20-20-20). Be sure to follow the instructions on the package for proper application rates.\n\nAs for the possibility of something in the soil stealing away the nitrogen, there are a few potential culprits. One possibility is that your soil has a high pH, which can make it more difficult for plants to absorb certain nutrients, including nitrogen. You can test your soil's pH and adjust it if necessary, using lime to raise the pH or sulfur to lower it.\n\nAnother possibility is that your soil has a high concentration of certain minerals, such as phosphorus or potassium, which can compete with",
